Corporation for Art and Television.
As JAM moved out of its second location, in Tribeca, the
need to develop a model of financial sustainability that
could protect artists' creative freedom became para-
mount for Linda Goode Bryant.' This pressure, as well
as the desire to "push [artists'] ideas and the tools they
used," led her to conceive the subsidiary Corporation
for Art and Television, or CAT. A for-profit production
facility to be housed at JAM's third home, in SoHo, it
would allow JAM to operate without relying on the typ-
ical financial models for both for-profit galleries and
nonprofit arts organizations. With CAT, JAM would be
able to divorce the need for income from the production
and presentation of art, and, in doing so, to safeguard its
mission from the demands of an art market increasingly
determined by an emerging class of Wall Street collec-
tors, as well as from the precarity inherent in fundraising
and pursuing grants.
CAT was imagined as a facility equipped with for-
rent production studios for video and audio, computer
animation, and photography. With a multitiered finan-
cial structure and advanced technological capabilities,
CAT would generate income that would in turn support
ambitious noncommercial programming catered to
artists working across mediums, in the fine arts and in
popular culture. The programming envisioned included
a television studio for "the presentation, broadcast,
and advancement of art"; think tanks to bring creatives
together to discuss the "intersection of art, technology,
and popular culture"; a publication "collaboratively pro-
duced by artists and writers"; and an artists' laboratory,
with participants benefitting from technical support and
a stipend. The plan for the first Laboratory Program,
for the 1984-85 season, which was partially realized,
included artists such as Chris Kraus, Christian Marclay,
Blondell Cummings, Senga Nengudi, Maren Hassinger,
Ralph Lemon, and David Hammons. The vision for CAT
was imbued with JAM's ethos of experimentation and
collaboration-the belief that those result from creative
practitioners coming together around a shared need for
studio space, materials, and curatorial support.
Though stacks of meticulous planning documents
for programming, budgets, and equipment were pro-
duced, CAT was never fully realized due to lack of fund-
ing and support from the local government. If it had, the
emphasis on emerging technologies would have taken
JAM in a new direction, one in step with the moment:
video equipment had become widely available a decade
earlier, and by 1985 the VCR was in fifty percent of
homes in the United States. Indeed, 1984, the year the
CAT Laboratory Program started, saw both Newsweek
and Time declaring the arrival of "the video revolution"
on their covers." Digital cameras and computers were
beginning to appear on the market at prices that were
more affordable for individuals, expanding possibil-
ities for artists working in media and technology and
for television as a venue for artistic expression. While
this shift is typically discussed in terms of individual
artistic production, CAT was an example of an arts
NONA HENDRYX
organization taking it on at an institutional level. The
earliest archival document that mentions CAT, "JAM
ReDesign: Conceptual Outline," states this outright,
declaring that "emphasis will be placed on concepts
and works which respond to or utilize (as palette) televi-
sion media." -MI
